text: From visionary filmmakers James Cameron (AVATAR) and Robert Rodriguez (SIN CITY), comes ALITA: BATTLE ANGEL, an epic adventure of hope and empowerment. When Alita (Rosa Salazar) awakens with no memory of who she is in a future world she does not recognize, she is taken in by Ido (Christoph Waltz), a compassionate doctor who realizes that somewhere in this abandoned cyborg shell is the heart and soul of a young woman with an extraordinary past. As Alita learns to navigate her new life and the treacherous streets of Iron City, Ido tries to shield her from her mysterious history while her street-smart new friend Hugo (Keean Johnson) offers instead to help trigger her memories. But it is only when the deadly and corrupt forces that run the city come after Alita that she discovers a clue to her past ‚Äì she has unique fighting abilities that those in power will stop at nothing to control. If she can stay out of their grasp, she could be the key to saving her friends, her family and the world she‚Äôs grown to love.

text: I'm a little scared of this. I have seen how hollywood changes original source materials in order to suit their own narratives and this story looks to be no different. The problems that we see here are kind of obvious. This is going to be a story of self discovery and loving some boy and becoming a female audience proxy. The anime centers around and unachievable goal of making a better lives for themselves by making their way to the city in the sky. The manga applies a much broader understanding of what the manga was trying to convey. Neither properties seem to be properly represented in this movie. So I will wait for the reviews. Then i will be able to tell if this is just another ghost in the shell or dragon ball z

author: kpro n

text: This is going to surprise, isn't it?  I ask that because I know if I feel like if it doesn't look good, it'll become great...for me though...because I mainly hate it that people can't like what I like and I want there to be fans of this film because it looks so rewarding to see Anime adaptations still trying to be done right. My favourite was Speed Racer...my biggest regret of viewing was Astro Boy, because they made it a shitty kids film. It should've been more mature by having a kid robot having to deal that he wasn't real and that his father hated him...god I hate Hollywood, but this time they're giving James Cameron a chance to prove that Anime adaptations can be good, if not, even greater. Robert Rodriguez isn't really my favourite director anymore, but it's good to see that he's taking lessons from James Cameron.  This film looks thin from the trailer...but the film itself will surprise me, and I'll look forward to me being wrong about it being bad or boring...here's to the unsuspecting surprise.

text: Honestly didn't expect them to get to motorball, but hell yeah to that. Some liberties being taken, but then some stuff straight from the anime or manga. The 'I'm an insignificant girl' line, straight from the end theme, heh. Would love for them to do more, but I honestly don't see it as practical... cramming 9 volumes of manga into movie-sized bites would be really hard, and that's not even counting 'Last Order'. So I could see them doing maybe a trilogy or quadrilogy, but that's it... and who knows how long that would take? I'd love to see who they'd get to play Desty Nova, though. Anyway, I'm just glad the 20+ years I've been waiting for this to actually happen were not in vain.

text: One big glaring issue I have with this film, (no it's not the eyes).   She's supposed to be a Cyborg, a human with enhanced body parts right? YET, she, or rather her head, where her organic human brain resides, is found in a junk heap.   We all know anything organic needs sustenance to transform into sugar to feed our living cells....  So, how can she have lain dormant, in a trash heap, with no digestive system, no food for said system, to feed her organic brain?   Because, she's NOT a Cyborg. She has to have an artificial brain, that runs on stored electrical current. She is an "it", an Android, in order to be deactivated/dormant for so long. She could have been fully human at one time, and in some circumstance had her mind/memories/essence transferred to this "brain", making her a she, maybe. But still, without at the minimum, an organic brain, she's not a Cyborg.

text: Did anyone else find this as a response to 'Captain Marvel'..?  This looks so much more like what a great female lead character could be, and she's not spending all of her time off-camera spewing racist, misandrist garbage out of her mouth.  Oddly enough, I was on Vice (I know, ugh) reading their take on the new Dissenter extension, and one of the things they said it would allow is people to comment on 'Captain Marvel' on Rotten Tomatoes. One of the Tweets featured in the article literally said something like "If you want something like this, without the SJW nonsense, see Alita Battle Angel.". I don't watch live TV anymore, so I miss 99% of movie trailers, I'm really glad I didn't miss this one!  Our dollars are the only real votes we have left, choose wisely.

text: THIS is what a strong female lead looks like! This movie had the BEST action sequences I have EVER seen. The movie's entire world is refreshingly new yet somehow excitingly familiar. There is SO much potential for this movie becoming a franchise and I sincerely hope that it gets the funding that it needs to do that. In a movie industry that seems to be running out of new ideas and has reverted to just remaking older movies, Alita: Battle Angel has opened up an entire world of new movie material. Alita has done what many movies before it failed to do: Create an exciting and meaningful sci-fi/cyberpunk movie.

text: To anyone like me, reading the comment section to see if this movie is worth your time, let me tell you: don't waste your time with this garbage.  Boring, stupid, cliche, full of plotholes the size of a truck, filled with awful forgettable characters, almost no action (and when there is, it's uninteresting) but a lot of awful teenage romance  that almost made me regret Twilight. Nothing makes sense, the worldbuilding is one of the worst I've ever seen and it's even a full movie but only a part 1, since almost nothing about the villain or Alita's past is explained.    Don't bother watching this. You want a smart cyborg movie? Check Ghost in the Shell (the anime). Want the story of a machine who grows into a good person: watch the Iron Giant or even Terminator 2. Want a good Robert Rodriguez movie? Watch Sin City or From Dusk till Dawn. Not this movie, who will be forgotten in a few years.

text: When people complain about modern movies, this is a perfect example of what they're complaining about: It's a movie with zero originality or anything else not done 100 times before. It's a movie made from the book of generic plots and over the the top CGI to distract from the fact it's the same movie they have seen before, where the most lethal weapon system on the planet happens to look like a cute teen age girl. It's Ready Player One meets The Running Man (and 80's Arnold movie for ye youngins out there..) and not in a good way. Dystopian post war future, gotta play a killer game to make it, yada yada. The visuals are impressive at times, but it does not make up fir this 200 million dollar pile of garbage for a movie. It's literally everything wrong with modern movies rolled into one shining example. Finally, it does not even try and pretend it's not made to be an ongoing franchise and leaves the viewer with zero satisfaction as to the ending... C+

In that time frame, they would have merged into one. The floating city is very vulnerable - just sever the anchors, and away it goes - presumably held up by a "space Elevator", but if so, then it MUST be located on the equator. And several more items . . . . . .
